Abstract: High speed switching networks have many applications in computer systems, including massively parallel processors, distributed multicomputers, networking and processor to disk interconnections. These applications all require high bandwidth, low latency communication paths. Although optical networks can meet these performance requirements, current circuit switching and packet switching techniques are not quite suitable for controlling such networks. Time division multiplexing (TDM) schemes can improve the performance of optical interconnection networks by taking advantage of the locality of references present in the communication patterns. In this paper, we construct a model to quantify the cost of compiled communications in multiplexed networks. We show how the cost is affected by the characteristics of the network and how to choose the most appropriate multiplexing degree based on these characteristics. To show how the cost is affected by the characteristics of a parallel application, we formally quantify the intuitive concept of locality of reference in communication patterns. We then relate locality to the communication costs in multiplexed networks. 
