Reference-contexts: TDM requires the use of a global clock to synchronize the time slots for all the transmitters and receivers connected to the network. The actual data transmission, however, does not require a global clock as self-clocking can be used at the bit level <ref> [2] </ref>. In parallel processing systems, the time required to communicate between processors is a significant factor affecting the performance of an application or algorithm. In a circuit-switched network, much of the communication delay arises from the network management overhead to provide the required paths. <p> Both determining and changing the network state are potential sources of communication delay. Techniques that determine the application's communication pattern and the required network states prior to program execution are called compiled communication, or static techniques <ref> [2, 12] </ref>. Techniques that use information gathered at program execution time to determine which paths the program needs are called dynamic techniques. The concepts of locality of reference and working set are well known in the context of a program's access to memory.
